# Respond to automated PR reviewers (Gemini Code Assist, Codex, similar)

Canonical merge bar and **substantive feedback** definition: `.cursor/rules/git-pr-workflow-default.mdc` (“PR review bots”).

Treat output from repo-integrated **automated code-review bots** as **required follow-up for communication**, not optional noise—especially:

- **Google Gemini Code Assist** (`gemini-code-assist`)
- **Codex** PR review when it appears as an automated reviewer on the PR (same expectations as Gemini)

Analogous bots (similar summaries, inline file comments, or suggestion blocks) fall under this rule unless listed in **Exceptions**.

## Wait before merge (hard)

**Never** squash-merge or enable **auto-merge** in the instant **`ci_result` turns green.** Complete the **Bot feedback wait gate** in `.cursor/rules/git-pr-workflow-default.mdc` first: late-review sweep via `gh pr view` / GitHub UI / API; **on github.com**, watch for PR UI cues (e.g. reactions/emojis or other signals that a bot review is **still being prepared**) and wait until those **settle**; if no substantive bot comments yet, **wait ~10–15 minutes** after green CI then **re-check** (Gemini, Copilot, Codex, and others often arrive **after** Actions finish). Merge only after that pause **and** threaded replies—or after an explicit human **waiver**.

## Required (mechanical checklist)

For each **substantive** bot point on a PR **you own**:

1. **Reply in-thread** on the comment or on the bot’s review summary (not only new commits).
2. Label the outcome in the reply: **implemented** (what changed; optional SHA), **deferred** (reason; link `docs/REFACTOR_BACKLOG.md` or issue if useful), or **declined / won’t do** (short merit-based reason).
3. Prefer a **small follow-up commit** when the change is straightforward; if you **defer** or **decline**, say so explicitly in that reply—do not rely on silence.

Do **not** merge with substantive Gemini **or Codex** feedback left **unanswered**.

## Exceptions

- Bot runs that are **SKIPPED**, **rate-limited with no review body**, or purely informational with **no actionable claims**: no reply needed (optional one-line “skipped” if useful).
- Points **already** covered by an earlier reply or commit: one bundled reply is enough (“Covered in commits above; …”).
- The **human maintainer** explicitly merges without bot closeout: assistants still default to replying when they control the PR.

## Relationship to CI

Green **`ci_result`** does **not** substitute for this rule; it governs **review conversation**, not build status.

## Rationale

Keeps GitHub review history auditable, respects high-signal automation from multiple vendors (Gemini and Codex), and separates “no code change” from “no response.”
